---
import Sigil from "./Sigil.astro";
---

<section id="daily-life" class="relative bg-marble bg-grain py-28 sm:py-36 px-6">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl">
    <div class="text-center">
      <p class="eyebrow">An Ordinary Tuesday</p>
      <h2 class="mt-4 font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl text-[var(--color-parchment)] tracking-wide">
        Daily Life in <span class="text-gold-gradient">Caltara</span>
      </h2>
      <Sigil class="mt-7" />
    </div>

    <div class="mt-14 space-y-6 text-[var(--color-parchment-dim)] leading-relaxed text-lg">
      <p>
        The city runs on coffee houses before it runs on anything else. The
        Ledger Quarter's clear favors and gossip over the same tables where
        Senate aides do it, and a working knowledge of which house serves
        which faction is closer to survival information than etiquette.
      </p>
      <p>
        Market days follow the tide, not the calendar — the harbor decides
        when the good catch and the foreign cargo come in, and the outer
        wards' stalls empty and refill accordingly. The Old Wards keep their
        own smaller, slower markets that haven't changed stock in a
        generation, which the families who shop there consider a feature.
      </p>
      <p>
        Founding Day, marking the Covenant's signing, is the one holiday the
        whole Republic actually observes the same way: a public reading of
        the Covenant's open clauses from the Ledger Steps, guild processions
        through the Old Wards, and a harbor-wide bonfire that Maren's clergy
        insists predates the Covenant itself.
      </p>
      <p>
        Temple attendance is a Sunday habit for most Caltarans and a load-
        bearing part of daily business for the rest — a contract witnessed
        before Thessar's altar, a duel sworn under Turak's rite, a captain's
        coin left for Maren before the tide turns. Nobody finds this
        unusual. It's simply how things get done here.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
